    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1960-04-26T08:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1960-04-26T08:30:00-05:00" n="170"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d170">
                <head>170. Memorandum of Conference With President <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                        >Eisenhower</persName>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d170fn0">Source: <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                            >Eisenhower</persName> Library, <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                            >Eisenhower</persName> Papers, DDE Diaries. Secret. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_WLCVA1">Walters</persName> on April 27. The meeting was held
                        in the Red Room at the White House when <persName corresp="#p_DEGC1">de
                            Gaulle</persName> called to say goodbye.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1960-04-26T08:30:00">April 26, 1960, 8:30
                            a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>OTHERS PRESENT</head>
                    <item>General <persName corresp="#p_DEGC1">de Gaulle</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_WLCVA1">Colonel Walters</persName>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>The President asked General <persName corresp="#p_DEGC1">de Gaulle</persName>
                    whether he had read <persName corresp="#p_KNS1">Khrushchev</persName>’s speech
                    at Baku<note n="1" xml:id="d170fn1">In <persName corresp="#p_KNS1"
                            >Khrushchev</persName>’s speech at Baku on April 25, he reiterated the
                        maximum Soviet demands on Germany and Berlin. For text, see <hi
                            rend="italic">Pravda</hi>, April 26, 1960.</note> and General <persName
                        corresp="#p_DEGC1">de Gaulle</persName> said he had. The President said that
                    one thing that bothered him about these speeches of <persName corresp="#p_KNS1"
                        >Khrushchev</persName>’s is that having taken these extremely firm positions
                    he found himself obliged to abide by them. General <persName corresp="#p_DEGC1"
                        >de Gaulle</persName> said that he did say these things, but he was not sure
                    he really meant them, and he did feel that sometime during the conference we
                    would probably have to say “No” to Mr. <persName corresp="#p_KNS1"
                        >Khrushchev</persName>, and the President nodded agreement.</p>
                <pb facs="0395" n="359" xml:id="pg_359"/>
                <p>On taking leave of the President, General <persName corresp="#p_DEGC1">de
                        Gaulle</persName> said “Now that I have seen you I have even greater
                    confidence in our cause.” The President replied, “We shall be standing
                    together.”</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WLCVA1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Vernon Walters</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="2" xml:id="d170fn2">Printed from a copy that bears this typed
                            signature.</note>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">Colonel U.S. Army</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
